  <sec id="SEC3">
    <title>RESULTS AND DISCUSSION</title>
    <sec id="SEC3-1">
      <title>Simulation</title>
      <p>We first demonstrate the utility of the proposed statistical model using simulated data. In all of the following examples we used <italic>e</italic><sub><italic>ir</italic></sub> = 0.001 as the default value and FDR threshold was set at <italic>f</italic><sub>0</sub> = 0.01. Also we assumed that the probability of observing more than two different alleles at a particular locus in a genome was considered rare. This is assumed because of the small chance of having a point mutation occurring twice at the same nucleotide (<xref rid="B33" ref-type="bibr">33</xref>–<xref rid="B35" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>). All of the simulation examples were based on short reads data generated for a single segment. Also, we only show examples with a small number of short reads. When a large number of reads were simulated, the proposed models performed very well, easily recovering the simulation truth. Tabulated posterior probabilities for all the scenarios are provided in the Supplementary Tables S1–S9.</p>
